      "note": "The chapter's rhetorical shape is tripartite: (A) ordination of persons (29:1-35) — washing, vesting, anointing, blood, eating, seven days; (B) consecration of altar and establishment of the daily offering (29:36-42) — daily bull, daily tamid, perpetual rhythm; (C) covenant ratification (29:43-46) — YHWH commits to meet, consecrate, dwell, and be known. The movement is from human action to divine declaration. What the elaborate human ritual cannot produce — actual holiness, actual divine dwelling — God claims with the three 'I will' statements of the chapter's close."
